<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-02-06T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-02-06T10:00:00-05:00" n="568" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d568">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">711.00111 <hi rend="superscript">Lic.
                                Wolf, Rudolf/51</hi>/47: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-02-06T15:00:00+00:00">February 6, 1937—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received February 6—12:52 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>174. Your 64, February 5, 2 p.m. Consul at Havre reports all the planes
                            still on the dock there. The plan to ship planes on the Greek steamer
                                <hi rend="italic">Katharictisa</hi> has apparently been abandoned as
                            that vessel sailed for Cardiff on February 3 without the planes.
                            According to stevedoring agents who were employed to handle the shipment
                            Hunzedal is endeavoring to arrange shipment to Marseille but French
                            customs office at Havre has received no instruction to issue permit thus
                            far. Shall telegraph further after hearing from Foreign Office.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>